Dear Paul Michel,

My name is Salem Ajluni, a resident of San Jose, CA, and I support the swift designation of the Chumash Heritage National Marine Sanctuary with the Initial Boundary Alternative and Gaviota Coast Extension to cover about 7,600 square miles of ocean proposed to protect biodiversity and habitats.

Perhaps the most beautiful segment of the California coastline is the Central Coast. It is a place me and my family have visited time and again to spend time on the beach and walk along the shoreline. We need that shoreline and ocean for recreation and to rejuvenate our minds and bodies. 

I support the designation of the Chumash Heritage National Marine Sanctuary. I ask that this sanctuary:  
1. be of the most expansive possible size but to include at least the The Initial Boundary Alternative with Gaviota Coast Extension; 
2. be named the "Chumash Heritage National Marine Sanctuary”;
3. be managed by all tribes of the Central Coast in an equitable manner under Collaborative Management; 
4. engages in outreach, education and research programs that elevate both Traditional Ecological Knowledge (TEK) and access for local underserved communities;
5. include the protection of Rodriguez Seamount as this is essential to protect its biodiversity;
6. prohibit any and all new oil and gas development within its boundaries;

I urge the Administration to designate the Chumash Heritage National Marine Sanctuary to allow current and future generations to enjoy, protect, and benefit from our ocean’s many treasures.

Sincerely,
Salem Ajluni
2317 Maywood Avenue
San Jose, CA 95128

Dear Paul Michel,

My name is Alex Barth and I support the swift designation of the Chumash Heritage National Marine Sanctuary with the Initial Boundary Alternative and Gaviota Coast Extension to cover about 7,600 square miles of ocean proposed to protect biodiversity and habitats.

I live near the coast and to me, the ocean is both a place to connect with nature, and a resource to educate the next generation about the ecological importance of our coastal habitats.

I support the designation of the Chumash Heritage National Marine Sanctuary. I ask that this sanctuary includes: 

Biggest Possible Boundary: The Initial Boundary Alternative with Gaviota Coast Extension;
The name “Chumash Heritage National Marine Sanctuary”;
 An equitable approach to include all Tribes in Collaborative Management;
Outreach, education and research programs that elevate both Traditional Ecological Knowledge (TEK) and access for local underserved communities; 
The protection of Rodriguez Seamount, which is essential to protect biodiversity;
And a prohibition on new oil and Gas development within sanctuary boundaries.
I support the designation of the Chumash Heritage National Marine Sanctuary. I urge the Administration to designate the Chumash Heritage National Marine Sanctuary to allow current and future generations to enjoy, protect, and benefit from our ocean’s many treasures.



Sincerely,

Alex Barth
